,"id":"107667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107667"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 39-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of progressive shortness of breath, productive cough with rusty sputum, fever, and pleuritic chest pain on the right side. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He denies any recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 91/min, blood pressure 122/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 21/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. Auscultation reveals decreased breath sounds and crackles over the right lower lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 141 g/L (135-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 16.7 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils: 12.3 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.8-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes: 3.5 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.0-3.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 12 mg/L (\u0026lt;3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray: consolidation in the right lower lobe\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESputum cultures have been sent and results are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following empirical antibiotics should be commenced?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Doxycycline","Amoxicillin","Azithromycin","Amoxicillin/clavulanic acid","Moxifloxacin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with community-acquired pneumonia (CAP). The rusty sputum, lobar consolidation, and acute presentation suggest pneumococcal pneumonia. According to Australian Therapeutic Guidelines, severity assessment is crucial for determining appropriate treatment. Markers of severity indicating need for admission include: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETachypnoea (respiratory rate \u0026gt;22)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETachycardia (heart rate \u0026gt;100bpm)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypotension (systolic blood pressure \u0026lt;90mmHg)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute onset confusion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOxygen saturation \u0026lt;92% on room air\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMultilobar involvement on chest X-ray\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood lactate concentration more than 2mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient exhibits no features for admission, he likely has low-severity pneumonia. For low-severity pneumococcal pneumonia, monotherapy with \u003Cstrong\u003Eamoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E 1 g orally three times daily for five days is the treatment of choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered for suspected atypical pneumonia, which typically presents more gradually with constitutional symptoms predominating over respiratory symptoms, and different radiographic features such as peribronchial opacity or patchy reticulonodular changes. In addition, doxycycline is recommended to be added to amoxicillin monotherapy if the patient fails to improve on monotherapy within 48 hours. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAzithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E serves as an alternative for pregnant patients with suspected atypical pneumonia, as doxycycline is contraindicated in pregnancy. It is not first-line for typical bacterial pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin/clavulanic acid\u003C/strong\u003E has no role in the empirical treatment of community-acquired pneumonia. The addition of clavulanic acid provides no benefit over amoxicillin alone for typical respiratory pathogens and is not recommended in guidelines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoxifloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with moderate-severity CAP who have had a severe (immediate or delayed) hypersensitivity reaction to penicillin. It would not be appropriate as first-line therapy in a patient without penicillin allergy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral amoxicillin is the treatment of choice for low-severity community-acquired pneumonia.","Moxifloxacin is used for moderate-severity community-acquired pneumonia in patients with severe penicillin hypersensitivity.","Amoxicillin/clavulanic acid has no role in the empirical treatment of community-acquired pneumonia."],"references":["Charles PG, Wolfe R, Whitby M, et al. SMART-COP: a tool for predicting the need for intensive respiratory or vasopressor support in community-acquired pneumonia. Clin Infect Dis. 2008;47(3):375-384. doi:10.1086/589754","Therapeutic Guidelines. (2023, June). Community-acquired pneumonia in adults. In Electronic therapeutic guidelines complete. Retrieved July 28, 2024, from https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Dueck NP, Epstein S, Franquet T, Moore CC, Bueno J. Atypical Pneumonia: Definition, Causes, and Imaging Features. Radiographics. 2021 May-Jun;41(3):720-741. doi: 10.1148/rg.2021200131. Available from: https://pubs.rsna.org/doi/full/10.1148/rg.2021200131"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13378"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T21:09:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T21:10:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5953"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107667"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d